d, include explicit low-yield and selectivity penalties in pathway reasoning\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.24,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.64,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.7,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.62,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.61,\n      \"feedback\": \"Phosphorylation of guanosine to GMP is broadly plausible in prebiotic chemistry, but this pathway inherits the major weakness of direct guanosine formation from free guanine and ribose. Since the nucleoside step is the true bottleneck, the full nucleotide pathway is not persuasive in its current form.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_017\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Rebuild this pathway on top of the FaPy-derived guanosine branch rather than direct glycosylation\",\n        \"Specify a more concrete phosphorylation chemistry and mineral context\",\n        \"Ensure the nucleotide route reflects the unified Becker et al. 2019 scenario if literature alignment is a goal\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a strong and ambitious network with good topology, meaningful hub selection, and real convergence on literature-relevant intermediates such as HCN, DAMN, AICN, AICA, formamide, and ribose. It captures the two most important guanine paradigms from the literature: the classical HCN oligomerization branch through AICN/AICA and the modern FaPy-based route to guanosine. It also correctly emphasizes that multiple environments likely contribute, especially hydrothermal generation of simple feedstocks, surface UV and drying chemistry, and biochemical-style assembly in concentrated settings.\\n\\nThe main limitations are chemical compression and a few misassignments. The hydrothermal precursor step is too broad and not tightly supported by the guanine literature; it functions more as a speculative feedstock generator than an experimentally established guanine-specific route. The AICA plus cyanate branch is incorrectly treated as guanine-producing when the literature more strongly supports hypoxanthine formation there. The FaPy branch captures the right idea but collapses several critical intermediates into one node and uses a self-loop that obscures chemical transformation. Direct guanine plus ribose glycosylation is included as if viable, but the literature identifies that route as a major unresolved problem with very poor yield and selectivity.\\n\\nTopology is good: the network is connected, has sufficient size, and contains multiple convergent target-reaching branches. Environmental interconnection is also good conceptually. However, because some target-reaching pathways rely on weak or inaccurate end steps, the network does not reach approval threshold for overall confidence. It is best viewed as a good literature-informed draft that needs correction of branch assignments and more explicit intermediate resolution in the FaPy and phosphorylation sections.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.88,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.9\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.58, "rxn_002": 0.72, "rxn_003": 0.9, "rxn_004": 0.95, "rxn_005": 0.93, "rxn_006": 0.86}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.86, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overall_confidence": 0.87, "feedback": "Strong literature-aligned HCN oligomerization trunk: HCN to DAMN, UV conversion to AICN, hydrolysis to AICA, then annulation with cyanogen to guanine is well supported by Ferris, Orgel, and Sanchez. Mai