state nitrosation with nitrite to generate stable nitroso-pyrimidines that physically enrich and feed the FaPy route (Becker et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Reduction of nitroso-pyrimidine to guanine FaPy precursor", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental iron in dilute formic acid", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycle sequence; nickel is reported in the literature but not represented as a node agent here"}, "mechanism": "Reductive opening/reorganization of the nitroso intermediate in formic acid furnishes the formamidopyrimidine precursor to guanosine.", "reasoning": "Reduction of dry-state nitroso intermediates with Fe/Ni in dilute formic acid to FaPys is a defining step of the Carell route; Fe0 is explicitly retained here to honor the reported chemistry while keeping the mineral list compatible (Becker et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "FaPy-ribose dry-state condensation to guanosine", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry-state condensation followed by basic aqueous rehydration; strong N9 regioselectivity"}, "mechanism": "The sugar is already associated with the ring-opened purine precursor, allowing purine ring closure onto ribose and yielding guanosine with high N9 selectivity.", "reasoning": "This is the key glycosylation-bypass route for guanine chemistry, giving about 60% N9-purine nucleoside yield and solving the major solubility/regiochemistry problem that plagues direct guanine-ribose coupling (Becker et al., 2016; Becker et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Hydrolysis of guanosine to guanine", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool hydrolysis or recycling of nucleosides"}, "mechanism": "Cleavage of the N-glycosidic bond releases free guanine and ribose, linking the nucleoside route back to the target base.", "reasoning": "Although the literature emphasizes guanosine formation rather than deliberate hydrolysis, inclusion of nucleoside/base interconversion is a necessary network connector that allows the validated FaPy route to feed the guanine node without invoking the known poor direct glycosylation route; this connector is therefore explicitly marked as a necessary but less directly documented completion step (Becker et al., 2016; Becker et al., 2019)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classical HCN oligomerization to guanine via cyanogen", "description": "Canonical Orgel-Ferris-Sanchez branch: HCN oligomerizes to DAMN, photoconverts to AICN, hydrolyzes to AICA, then annulates with cyanogen to guanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-fed HCN route to guanine", "description": "Hydrothermal formate generation feeds surface formamide/HCN production, then enters the canonical AICN/AICA/cyanogen branch to guanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Eutectic-concentrated HCN route with dry-state AICA closure", "description": "HCN concentration in ice or evaporitic channels gives DAMN and AICN, followed by AICA formation and lower-certainty dry-state closure with urea to guanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Thermal formamide mineral route", "description": "Neat formamide heated with productive minerals such as pyrite yields guanine through a distributed self-catalytic reaction network.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "UV-enhanced formamide route", "description": "UV irradiation of hot concentrated formamide produces guanine without requiring the full explicit HCN trunk in the network representation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "High-energy formamide route", "description": "Impact/plasma or proton-irradiated formamide gives guanine through CN-radical chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "TAHP drying route to guanine", "description": "HCN-derived aminopyrimidine chemistry forms TAHP, which cyclizes to guanine in a urea-ammonium-formate-water drying system.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Carell FaPy route from HCN-derived aminopyrimidines to guanosine then guanine", "description": "HCN-derived TAHP is nitrosated, reduced to a guanine FaPy precursor, condensed with ribose to guanosine, then hydrolyzed to free guanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_017", "mol_022", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal-fed Carell route", "description": "Hydrothermal C1 reduction feeds surface formamide and HCN, which then support aminopyrimidine formation, FaPy chemistry, guanosine assembly, and release of guanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_015", "mol_022", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Integrated ribose-enabled FaPy r