{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T14:58:35.919701", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Guanine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Guanine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of guanine: routes, evidence, and unsolved puzzles\n\n**Guanine (C\u2085H\u2085N\u2085O) is among the hardest canonical nucleobases to synthesize under plausible prebiotic conditions**, consistently produced at 10\u201340\u00d7 lower yields than adenine across virtually all known pathways. Yet extraterrestrial samples tell a different story: recent meteorite analyses reveal guanine as the most abundant purine nucleobase in some carbonaceous chondrites, reaching **649 ppb in Murchison** (Koga et al. 2024, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*). This paradox \u2014 difficult terrestrial synthesis but abundant extraterrestrial occurrence \u2014 frames one of prebiotic chemistry's central puzzles. Multiple synthesis routes now exist, from Or\u00f3's classic HCN oligomerization to Carell's high-yielding formamidopyrimidine (FaPy) pathway, but each carries constraints on environmental context, reagent availability, and selectivity. This report covers the full landscape of known pathways, intermediates, conditions, catalysts, experimental evidence, astrochemical context, and open challenges relevant to building synthesis network models for guanine.\n\n---\n\n## HCN oligomerization: the foundational pathway from five molecules of HCN\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of purines from hydrogen cyanide remains the most thoroughly studied route, originating with John Or\u00f3's landmark 1960 demonstration that concentrated ammonium cyanide produces adenine. Guanine synthesis via this route was definitively established only in 1999, when Levy, Miller, and Or\u00f3 showed that NH\u2084CN polymerization yields guanine at both **+80\u00b0C and \u221220\u00b0C**, albeit at **10\u201340\u00d7 lower yields** than adenine (*Journal of Molecular Evolution* 49, 165\u2013168).\n\nThe stepwise mechanism, refined by Ferris and Orgel through the 1960s, proceeds through four oligomerization steps before a critical branching point:\n\n**Step 1\u20134 (shared trunk):** HCN dimerizes to iminoacetonitrile, adds a third HCN to form aminomalononitrile (AMN), then a fourth to produce **diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN)** \u2014 a stable, crystalline HCN tetramer (C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084). DAMN formation requires HCN concentrations above ~0.01 M, below which hydrolysis to formamide dominates. Under UV irradiation (~350 nm), DAMN photoisomerizes to its trans-isomer (diaminofumaronitrile, DAFN), which thermally cyclizes to **4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile (AICN)** \u2014 with conversion efficiencies of **77\u201382%** (Ferris & Orgel 1966, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 88, 1074). Quantum yields for the DAMN\u2192DAFN step are approximately 0.045, and for DAFN\u2192AICN approximately 0.0034 (Szabla et al. 2014, *Chemistry \u2013 A European Journal*).\n\n**Step 5 \u2014 the critical divergence:** AICN is the central branch point determining whether adenine or guanine forms. If AICN reacts with HCN or formamidine before hydrolysis, it yields **adenine** via ring closure. If AICN undergoes hydrolysis first, the nitrile group converts to an amide, producing **AICA (4-aminoimidazole-5-carboxamide)**. AICA then reacts with cyanogen (NCCN), cyanate (OCN\u207b), or urea to close the pyrimidine ring and yield **guanine** (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel 1968, *Journal of Molecular Biology* 38, 121\u2013128). This hydrolysis requirement is the fundamental reason guanine yields trail adenine \u2014 aqueous conditions favor hydrolysis but also compete with the HCN addition that leads to adenine.\n\nThe overall pentamerization 5 HCN \u2192 adenine is highly exothermic (\u0394G\u2082\u2089\u2088 = **\u221253.7 kcal/mol**; Roy, Najafian & Schleyer 2007, *PNAS*). For guanine, the thermodynamics are similarly favorable but the kinetic pathway is longer and requires an oxygen-incorporating step. Computational analysis by Jung and Choe (2018, *Chemical Physics Letters*) mapped the potential energy surface for guanine formation from AICN + H\u2082O + NCCN, finding high gas-phase barriers that are significantly reduced by water molecule catalysis.\n\n---\n\n## Formamide routes produce guanine through a self-catalytic network\n\nFormamide (HCONH\u2082) serves as both solvent and reactant \u2014 a liquid between 4\u2013211\u00b0C that thermally decomposes to HCN + H\u2082O, generating the same oligomerization intermediates as aqueous HCN chemistry but in a concentrated, non-aqueous medium. The Italian school led by Raffaele Saladino and Ernesto Di Mauro systematically explored formamide-based nucleobase synthesis beginning in 2001.\n\nHeating neat formamide at **160\u00b0C for 48 hours** with mineral catalysts (TiO\u2082, CaCO\u2083, montmorillonite, iron-sulfur minerals, meteorite powders) produces panels of nucleobases, amino acids, and carboxylic acids whose composition depends on the specific catalyst (Saladino et al. 2001, *Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry*; 2003, *ChemBioChem*; 2008, *JACS* 130, 15512). Guanine yields from thermal-only formamide experiments are generally trace to sub-percent, with adenine and hypoxanthine more abundant. However, **UV irradiation dramatically enhances guanine production**. Barks, Hud, Orlando, and Di Mauro (2010, *ChemBioChem* 11, 1240\u20131243) demonstrated that neat formamide irradiated at **254 nm and 130\u00b0C** produces adenine, hypoxanthine, and guanine even without mineral catalysts, effectively \"relaxing the requirements\" for purine nucleobase formation.\n\nProton irradiation experiments simulating cosmic ray bombardment represent another energy source. Saladino et al. (2015, *PNAS* 112, E2746\u2013E2755) irradiated formamide with **165 MeV proton beams** in the presence of powdered meteorites and detected an extraordinarily rich product panel: amino acids, carboxylic acids, nucleobases (including guanine), sugars, and four nucleosides. High-energy laser-induced plasma experiments by Ferus et al. (2015, *PNAS* 112, 657\u2013662) similarly produced all four canonical nucleobases from formamide, establishing radical cyanide (CN\u2022) pathways as a \"unified mechanism\" for nucleobase formation under impact conditions.\n\nComputational work by Slavova et al. (2020, *International Journal of Quantum Chemistry*) mapped complete reaction pathways from pure formamide to all six major purines (adenine, guanine, hypoxanthine, xanthine, isoguanine, 2,6-diaminopurine), showing that all needed reactants and catalysts \u2014 HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082O, formic acid, urea, formimidic acid \u2014 arise from partial decomposition of formamide itself, constituting a self-catalytic system.\n\n---\n\n## Carell's FaPy pathway achieves 60% nucleoside yield with strict regioselectivity\n\nThe most significant recent advance in prebiotic guanine chemistry comes from Thomas Carell's group at LMU Munich. In 2016, Becker, Thoma, Deutsch, Gehrke, Mayer, Zipse, and Carell reported that **formamidopyrimidines (FaPys) condense with ribose to produce N9-purine nucleosides with ~60% yield and extreme regioselectivity** (*Science* 352, 833\u2013836). This addressed the long-standing \"glycosylation problem\" \u2014 the difficulty of attaching purine bases to ribose with correct regiochemistry.\n\nThe FaPy precursors are themselves prebiotically accessible: HCN oligomers react with guanidine and formic acid to yield aminopyrimidines, which are formylated to produce FaPy intermediates. For guanine specifically, the FaPy derived from **2,5,6-triamino-4-hydroxypyrimidine** yields guanosine with correct N9-regiochemistry upon dry-state condensation with ribose, followed by rehydration under basic conditions.\n\nThe Carell group extended this work in two landmark papers. Becker et al. (2018, *Nature Communications* 9, 163) demonstrated that **wet-dry cycles** \u2014 a regular feature of geothermal field environments \u2014 drive the entire sequence: aminopyrimidines react with sodium nitrite in the dry state to form nitroso-pyrimidines (stable, high-melting, insoluble compounds that physically enrich by precipitation). Reduction with elemental iron and nickel in dilute formic acid yields FaPys, which condense with ribose upon drying to produce canonical and non-canonical purine nucleosides. Three sequential physical enrichment steps driven by solubility differences provide a natural purification mechanism.\n\nIn 2019, Becker et al. (*Science* 366, 76\u201382) connected the purine pathway with pyrimidine synthesis, demonstrating the first **unified prebiotically plausible synthesis of all four Watson-Crick nucleosides** (adenosine, guanosine, cytidine, uridine) plus their 5\u2032-mono- and diphosphates under consistent geochemical conditions. Hydroxylamine \u2014 formed from nitrite and sulfite at ~70\u00b0C in 27\u201337% yield \u2014 serves as the key starting material linking all pathways. This represents the current state of the art in prebiotic nucleotide synthesis.\n\n---\n\n## Cyanosulfidic chemistry produces adenine but not guanine\n\nThe elegant cyanosulfidic network developed by John Sutherland's group at MRC Cambridge has attracted enormous attention since the landmark Patel et al. (2015) paper demonstrating common origins of RNA, protein, and lipid precursors from HCN derivatives, H\u2082S, and UV-driven Cu(I)\u2013Cu(II) photoredox cycling (*Nature Chemistry* 7, 301\u2013307). However, **this network does not produce guanine or guanosine**. The purine branch yields adenosine, deoxyadenosine, inosine (hypoxanthine base), and deoxyinosine, but not guanine-containing species (Xu et al. 2020, *Nature* 582, 60\u201366; Xu et al. 2021, *JACS*). Guanine incorporation into the cyanosulfidic framework remains an open challenge.\n\nMatthew Powner's contributions include chemoselective multicomponent assembly of purine precursors in water (2011, *JACS*), demonstrating pH-dependent reactions using 2-aminooxazole and 5-aminoimidazoles that produce only N9-purination \u2014 a key regiochemical requirement. Stairs et al. (2017, *Nature Communications* 8, 15270) showed divergent synthesis of pyrimidine and **8-oxo-purine ribonucleotides** from common precursors, offering an alternative where 8-oxo-guanine nucleotides, which are well-tolerated in Watson-Crick base pairs with cytosine, might have served as primitive guanine surrogates.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates form a branching network connecting all purines\n\nThe pathway from simple molecules to guanine passes through a network of intermediates that also connect to adenine, hypoxanthine, xanthine, and non-canonical purines. Understanding these branch points is essential for synthesis network modeling.\n\n| Intermediate | Formula | Role | Branch point? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HCN | CHN | C\u2081N\u2081 building block | \u2014 |\n| Aminomalononitrile (AMN) | C\u2083H\u2083N\u2083 | HCN trimer; highly reactive | Minor |\n| **DAMN** (diaminomaleonitrile) | C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 | HCN tetramer; stable crystalline solid | **Major**: UV \u2192 AICN; thermal \u2192 polymers; + formamidine \u2192 pentamer |\n| **AICN** (4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile) | C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 | Central purine precursor; photostable | **Major**: + HCN \u2192 adenine; + H\u2082O \u2192 AICA \u2192 guanine |\n| **AICA** (4-aminoimidazole-5-carboxamide) | C\u2084H\u2086N\u2084O | Hydrolysis product of AICN | **Major**: + cyanogen \u2192 guanine; + cyanate \u2192 hypoxanthine |\n| Formamidine | CH\u2084N\u2082 | One-carbon N-donor | Directs to adenine |\n| Cyanamide | CH\u2082N\u2082 | Condensing agent; detected in ISM | Multiple heterocycles |\n| Guanidine | CH\u2085N\u2083 | From HCN polymer hydrolysis | Annulation to guanine derivatives |\n| Hypoxanthine | C\u2085H\u2084N\u2084O | 6-oxopurine; deamination product of adenine | \u2192 xanthine or guanine |\n| Xanthine | C\u2085H\u2084N\u2084O\u2082 | 2,6-dioxopurine | \u2192 guanine via amination |\n| FaPy (formamidopyrimidines) | Variable | Ring-opened purine precursor | Carell pathway to A, G nucleosides |\n\nThe adenine-guanine interconversion pathway \u2014 adenine \u2192 hypoxanthine (deamination) \u2192 xanthine (oxidation) \u2192 guanine (amination) \u2014 is thermodynamically characterized but kinetically extremely slow under ambient conditions. Adenine deamination has a half-life of ~80 years at 37\u00b0C, pH 7 (Shapiro 1995). Computational modeling shows the gas-phase barrier for the full adenine\u2192guanine transition is prohibitive (k \u2248 5.59 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2074\u2070 s\u207b\u00b9), though individual steps like deamination are thermodynamically favorable in water (\u0394G = \u22129.63 kcal/mol).\n\nA noteworthy recent contribution from Menor-Salv\u00e1n, Hud, and colleagues (2022, *Chemistry \u2013 A European Journal*) demonstrated guanine formation from **2,5,6-triamino-4-hydroxypyrimidine** in urea-ammonium-formate-water solvent dried at 65\u00b0C over 3 days. They also produced **2,4-diaminopurine in 60% yield** from tetraaminopyrimidine, establishing a unified prebiotic context linking pyrimidines, pterins, and purines.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions that favor each synthesis step\n\nThree principal environments have been experimentally validated for different stages of the guanine synthesis network, and each carries distinct advantages and limitations.\n\n**Eutectic freezing (\u22122 to \u221278\u00b0C)** resolves the critical concentration problem for HCN chemistry. The water-HCN eutectic at **\u221223.4\u00b0C** concentrates HCN from dilute solution into liquid channels between ice crystals, reaching the \u22650.01 M threshold required for polymerization. Miyakawa, Cleaves, and Miller (2002, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 32, 209\u2013218) demonstrated this definitively: NH\u2084CN frozen at \u221278\u00b0C for **27 years** yielded 11 purines and pyrimidines upon hydrolysis, including adenine, guanine, hypoxanthine, xanthine, and 2,6-diaminopurine. Even initial concentrations as low as **0.001 M** proved sufficient under eutectic conditions. Schwartz, Joosten, and Voet (1982, *BioSystems*) and Levy et al. (2000) independently confirmed purine production from frozen HCN. This environment also maximizes nucleobase stability: at 0\u00b0C, guanine's half-life exceeds **10\u2076 years** versus ~1 year at 100\u00b0C (Levy & Miller 1998, *PNAS* 95, 7933).\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools with wet-dry cycling (20\u201380\u00b0C)** provide the environment best suited for the Carell FaPy pathway and for nucleoside formation. Evaporation concentrates reactants by factors of ~**1,400\u00d7** (Ross & Deamer 2016). The dry state enables condensation reactions (glycosidic bond formation, phosphorylation) that are thermodynamically unfavorable in bulk water. UV-C radiation \u2014 approximately **10\u00d7 more intense** on the ozone-free early Earth \u2014 drives the DAMN\u2192AICN photochemical conversion essential for purine synthesis while simultaneously providing a selection pressure favoring photostable nucleobases. A 2025 study (*ACS Central Science*) showed 2\u2032,3\u2032-cyclic nucleotides polymerize under wet-dry cycling at room temperature with yields of ~70% for guanosine monomers at mildly alkaline pH 10\u201311.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311)** offer sustained chemical energy from serpentinization and mineral catalysts (FeS, Fe\u2083S\u2084, Ni-mackinawite) at the vent-ocean interface. The Martin and Russell model proposes that the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway supplies all intermediates for purine and pyrimidine biosynthesis. However, nucleobase stability constrains this setting: at 100\u00b0C, adenine and guanine half-lives are approximately **1 year**, and cytosine's is only **19 days** (Levy & Miller 1998). Black smoker temperatures (300\u2013400\u00b0C) are incompatible with nucleobase accumulation entirely.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts steer product selectivity in formamide and HCN chemistry\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** \u2014 pyrite (FeS\u2082), greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), mackinawite (FeS), pyrrhotite, and chalcopyrite (CuFeS\u2082) \u2014 catalyze nucleobase synthesis from formamide at 160\u00b0C (Saladino et al. 2008, *JACS* 130, 15512). Pyrite gives the highest yields of purine, adenine, and 2-aminopurine. Different iron-sulfur minerals produce distinct selectivity profiles, with some favoring purines and others pyrimidines. An important caveat: these same minerals catalyze **RNA degradation** with half-lives as short as 1.8 minutes in formamide, raising questions about polymer survival.\n\n**Clay minerals**, especially Na\u207a-montmorillonite, play dual roles: concentrating reactants through adsorption and catalyzing oligomerization. James Ferris's group at RPI demonstrated that montmorillonite catalyzes RNA oligomer formation up to **50-mers** from activated mononucleotides with addition of fresh monomer over 14 days (Huang & Ferris 2006, *JACS* 128, 8914). Purine nucleotides preferentially form the biologically relevant **3\u2032,5\u2032-phosphodiester bonds** on clay surfaces, while pyrimidines favor 2\u2032,5\u2032-linkages. Relative reactivity of activated monomers follows A > G > C > U (ratio 8.2:4.8:1.3:1).\n\n**Titanium dioxide (TiO\u2082)** acts as a UV-responsive semiconductor photocatalyst. Senanayake and Idriss (2006, *PNAS* 103, 1194) showed that formamide adsorbed on TiO\u2082(001) single-crystal surfaces produced mass spectrometric signals consistent with adenine (m/z 135), **guanine (m/z 151)**, uracil (m/z 112), and cytosine (m/z 111) upon **3.2 eV** illumination \u2014 band-gap excitation of the semiconductor rather than direct molecular photolysis, allowing product accumulation without photodestruction.\n\n**Borate minerals** primarily stabilize ribose rather than directly catalyzing purine ring formation. Ricardo, Carrigan, Olcott, and Benner (2004, *Science* 303, 196) showed borate complexation at the 2\u2032,3\u2032-hydroxyl positions selectively stabilizes ribose over other aldopentoses, an essential enabler for nucleoside formation. Furukawa et al. (2022, *Scientific Reports*) achieved high-yield regioselective ribose 5\u2032-phosphate synthesis from ribose, phosphate, urea, and borate via thermal evaporation \u2014 phosphorylation greatest for ribose and **only in borate's presence**. Tourmaline, a boron-rich mineral, has been found in >3.7 Ga metasediments in Isua, Greenland, confirming early geological availability.\n\n---\n\n## Quantitative experimental evidence across six decades\n\nThe experimental record for prebiotic guanine synthesis spans from Or\u00f3's 1960 experiments to 2026 asteroid sample analyses:\n\n| Experiment | Conditions | Guanine outcome | Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| NH\u2084CN polymerization (warm) | 1 M, 80\u00b0C, days | ~0.01\u20130.05% yield (10\u201340\u00d7 less than adenine) | Levy, Miller & Or\u00f3 1999, *J. Mol. Evol.* |\n| NH\u2084CN frozen 27 years | 0.15 M, \u221278\u00b0C | Detected by GC/MS after hydrolysis | Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller 2002, *OLEB* |\n| AICN \u2192 AICA \u2192 guanine | UV + aqueous + cyanogen | Demonstrated stepwise | Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel 1968, *J. Mol. Biol.* |\n| Formamide + UV (254 nm) | 130\u00b0C, 48 h, neat | Detected without catalyst | Barks et al. 2010, *ChemBioChem* |\n| Formamide + TiO\u2082 surface | UHV, 3.2 eV light | m/z 151 detected | Senanayake & Idriss 2006, *PNAS* |\n| Formamide + proton beam | 165 MeV, meteorite catalyst | Part of rich product panel | Saladino et al. 2015, *PNAS* |\n| Laser plasma (impact sim.) | High-energy, formamide | All 4 canonical bases by GC-MS | Ferus et al. 2015, *PNAS* |\n| FaPy + ribose (dry state) | 100\u00b0C dry, then basic aqueous | **~60% N9-nucleoside yield** | Becker et al. 2016, *Science* |\n| Unified wet-dry synthesis | Geothermal model, Fe/Ni | All 4 nucleosides + phosphates | Becker et al. 2019, *Science* |\n| Murchison meteorite | Extraterrestrial | **649 \u00b1 103 ppb** (6M HCl extract) | Koga et al. 2024, *GCA* |\n| Ryugu asteroid (Hayabusa2) | Returned sample | All 5 canonical bases detected | Oba et al. 2026, *Nature Astronomy* |\n\nOr\u00f3's original 1960\u20131961 papers (*Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications* 2, 407; *Archives of Biochemistry and Biophysics* 94, 217) did not specifically report guanine \u2014 the **6N HCl hydrolysis** protocol used to maximize adenine yield actually decomposes guanine. Detection of guanine from HCN chemistry required milder hydrolysis conditions, achieved only decades later. Meteorite analyses provide the strongest quantitative evidence for prebiotic guanine abundance: Callahan et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108, 13995) found guanine at **244 ppb** in CM2 meteorite LON 94102 \u2014 the most abundant canonical nucleobase in that sample. Three terrestrially rare analogs (purine, 2,6-diaminopurine, 6,8-diaminopurine) found alongside canonical bases but absent from surrounding soil provided the definitive contamination control. Carbon isotope ratios (\u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C = +44.5\u2030 for meteoritic nucleobases vs. \u221210.6\u2030 for soil; Martins et al. 2008, *Earth and Planetary Science Letters*) independently confirm extraterrestrial origin.\n\n---\n\n## Guanine precursors pervade the interstellar medium and comets\n\nHCN \u2014 the ultimate starting material for purine synthesis \u2014 is one of the most abundant carbon-containing molecules in the interstellar medium, detected ubiquitously in molecular clouds, star-forming regions, comets, and planetary atmospheres. **Formamide (NH\u2082CHO)** was first detected in the dense cloud Sgr B2 (Rubin et al. 1971, *Astrophysical Journal*) and has since been found across the Galactic Habitable Zone (Adande et al. 2013, *Astrobiology* 13, 439). Additional detected precursors include cyanamide (NH\u2082CN), cyanomethanimine (HNCHCN \u2014 the HCN dimer; Rivilla et al. 2019), glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN; Zeng et al. 2019), and aminoacetonitrile (Belloche et al. 2008). Over 256 molecular species have been identified in the ISM to date, though no nucleobase has been directly detected there.\n\nCometary inventories are equally rich. The Rosetta mission detected HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, methanol, formic acid, glycine, methylamine, ethylamine, and phosphorus in comet 67P's coma (Altwegg et al. 2016, *Science Advances*). Ammonium cyanide (NH\u2084CN) \u2014 the precise reagent of Or\u00f3's purine synthesis \u2014 was identified in 67P dust particles. Formamide is present at ~0.01% relative to water in comets. However, **guanine itself has not been directly detected in any comet**; mass spectrometer resolution aboard spacecraft is currently insufficient for unambiguous nucleobase identification.\n\nExtraterrestrial delivery estimates from Chyba and Sagan (1992, *Nature* 355, 125) suggest that interplanetary dust particles may have delivered **\u226510\u2076\u201310\u2077 kg/yr** of intact organics to the early Earth, with the caveat that organics do not survive impacts above ~10 km/s. Late Heavy Bombardment (~4.5\u20133.8 Ga) both delivered and destroyed organics, creating a complex temporal window. The detection of all five canonical nucleobases in Ryugu asteroid return samples (Oba et al. 2026, *Nature Astronomy*) \u2014 with purine-to-pyrimidine ratios varying systematically with ammonia content across different parent bodies \u2014 confirms that nucleobase synthesis occurs in asteroidal aqueous alteration environments and delivery to Earth was plausible.\n\n---\n\n## Four persistent challenges define the frontier of prebiotic guanine research\n\n**The selectivity problem** remains largely unresolved. No single prebiotic scenario consistently produces guanine in high yield relative to other purines. In HCN oligomerization, the product hierarchy follows adenine >> hypoxanthine > purine > 2,6-diaminopurine > guanine > xanthine (Callahan et al. 2011, normalized to adenine = 1: guanine \u2248 0.02). This reflects the additional hydrolysis and ring-closure steps required for guanine. Mineral catalysts, UV irradiation, and specific temperature regimes shift product distributions but do not achieve selective guanine production. Whether selectivity is even necessary remains debated \u2014 W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user proposed an all-purine precursor to nucleic acids, and hypoxanthine can base-pair with cytosine as a guanine surrogate.\n\n**The concentration problem** has been partially resolved through eutectic freezing. Miyakawa et al. (2002) calculated steady-state HCN concentration in a warm (100\u00b0C, pH 8) primitive ocean at only **7 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M** \u2014 far below the \u22650.01 M needed for polymerization. Eutectic freezing at \u221223.4\u00b0C concentrates HCN by >100-fold in liquid veins between ice crystals. Evaporitic pools, mineral adsorption on clays and hydroxylapatite, and thermophoretic concentration of formamide in hydrothermal pores (Niether et al. 2016, *PNAS*) offer complementary concentration mechanisms. Whether sufficient frozen or evaporitic environments existed on the Hadean Earth remains debated.\n\n**Stability constraints** set a temperature ceiling. Guanine's half-life at 100\u00b0C and pH 7 is approximately **1 year**, decomposing to xanthine via deamination (Levy & Miller 1998, *PNAS*). At 0\u00b0C, the half-life extends to ~1.3 \u00d7 10\u2076 years \u2014 marginally adequate for low-temperature origin scenarios. For comparison, cytosine is far less stable (t\u2081/\u2082 = 19 days at 100\u00b0C, 17,000 years at 0\u00b0C), making cytosine the most vulnerable component of the Watson-Crick base-pair system. Guanine's remarkable **UV photostability** \u2014 arising from ultrafast internal conversion via peaked conical intersections \u2014 may have provided a selection advantage on the UV-drenched early Earth.\n\n**The glycosylation challenge is arguably the hardest remaining problem for guanine specifically.** Direct coupling of free guanine with ribose gives extremely low yields (Kim & Benner 2017, *PNAS*: only **0.34% guanosine 2\u2032-phosphate** from ribose 1,2-cyclic phosphate plus guanine), primarily because of guanine's very low aqueous solubility. Multiple N-nucleophilic sites create regiochemistry problems (N7 vs. N9), and anomeric (\u03b1 vs. \u03b2) and ring-size (furanose vs. pyranose) selectivity must also be controlled. The Carell FaPy pathway circumvents these issues by building the purine ring onto a pre-attached sugar, achieving ~60% N9-selective nucleoside formation. Powner's tethered glycosylation approach produces 8-oxo-purine ribonucleotides as potential guanine surrogates. The Sutherland cyanosulfidic network avoids the glycosylation problem for pyrimidines entirely but has not yet incorporated guanine.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: converging pathways and the road ahead\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of guanine is no longer a matter of \"if\" but \"how, where, and how much.\" At least five experimentally demonstrated routes exist \u2014 HCN oligomerization, formamide thermolysis/photolysis, FaPy condensation, impact/plasma chemistry, and extraterrestrial parent-body aqueous processing \u2014 each operating under different environmental conditions and producing guanine through distinct intermediate networks that share common early steps. The field is converging on integrated scenarios combining multiple environments: eutectic freezing for HCN concentration, UV irradiation for the DAMN\u2192AICN conversion, wet-dry cycling for nucleoside formation via FaPy intermediates, and mineral catalysis for selectivity tuning.\n\nThree insights stand out for synthesis network modeling. First, **AICN is the master branch point** \u2014 its fate (HCN addition vs. hydrolysis) determines adenine vs. guanine selectivity, making water activity the critical control parameter. Second, the **FaPy pathway represents a paradigm shift** from \"base-first\" to \"base-on-sugar\" assembly, achieving yields and regioselectivity unmatched by any other prebiotic purine route. Third, meteorite data consistently show guanine as the dominant purine in certain parent bodies, suggesting that aqueous alteration chemistry on asteroids may be more efficient at guanine production than any terrestrial laboratory simulation to date \u2014 a finding that should inform model calibration. The principal remaining bottleneck is not guanine synthesis per se but rather its efficient, selective incorporation into nucleotides under a unified, geochemically coherent scenario.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: This is a strong and ambitious network with good topology, meaningful hub selection, and real convergence on literature-relevant intermediates such as HCN, DAMN, AICN, AICA, formamide, and ribose. It captures the two most important guanine paradigms from the literature: the classical HCN oligomerization branch through AICN/AICA and the modern FaPy-based route to guanosine. It also correctly emphasizes that multiple environments likely contribute, especially hydrothermal generation of simple feedstocks, surface UV and drying chemistry, and biochemical-style assembly in concentrated settings.\n\nThe main limitations are chemical compression and a few misassignments. The hydrothermal precursor step is too broad and not tightly supported by the guanine literature; it functions more as a speculative feedstock generator than an experimentally established guanine-specific route. The AICA plus cyanate branch is incorrectly treated as guanine-producing when the literature more strongly supports hypoxanthine formation there. The FaPy branch captures the right idea but collapses several critical intermediates into one node and uses a self-loop that obscures chemical transformation. Direct guanine plus ribose glycosylation is included as if viable, but the literature identifies that route as a major unresolved problem with very poor yield and selectivity.\n\nTopology is good: the network is connected, has sufficient size, and contains multiple convergent target-reaching branches. Environmental interconnection is also good conceptually. However, because some target-reaching pathways rely on weak or inaccurate end steps, the network does not reach approval threshold for overall confidence. It is best viewed as a good literature-informed draft that needs correction of branch assignments and more explicit intermediate resolution in the FaPy and phosphorylation sections.\n- Issues: ['The route is coherent up to AICA, but the terminal annulation step is misassigned. Literature cited in the research summary indicates AICA plus cyanogen gives guanine, whereas AICA plus cyanate is associated mainly with hypoxanthine rather than guanine. Because the network claims direct guanine formation here, target achievement is weak.', 'This pathway is reasonably aligned with older AICA plus urea chemistry and with newer drying-system purine work, but the direct mapping from AICA plus urea to guanine is less canonical and less strongly supported than the cyanogen route. It is plausible as a drying-system branch, yet the network does not provide enough detail on conditions or competing products.', 'Formamide thermolysis on iron-sulfur minerals to guanine is supported in broad terms by Saladino and coworkers, with pyrite among productive catalysts. However, the pathway is overcompressed: the chemistry proceeds through a complex network of HCN, NH3, water, urea, formic acid, and related intermediates rather than a single-step clean conversion. The upstream hydrothermal generation of formamide remains the least secure feature.', 'TiO2-assisted photochemistry from formamide to guanine is literature-supported, but the original evidence is surface-science oriented and not a full high-yield geochemical network. As drawn, the pathway is plausible but somewhat simplified and dependent on a poorly justified hydrothermal formamide source.', 'Impact/plasma formamide chemistry can yield guanine and is experimentally documented, but classifying it simply as a standard surface pathway is somewhat loose because the energy source is exceptional and transient. The path is plausible as an episodic source, not as a routine dominant route.', 'This is the weakest target-reaching route because direct glycosylation of free guanine with ribose is a major known bottleneck. The literature explicitly identifies guanine glycosylation as extremely poor due to low solubility and regioselectivity issues, with very low reported yields. Thus the pathway reaches guanosine only nominally, not convincingly.', 'Phosphorylation of guanosine to GMP is broadly plausible in prebiotic chemistry, but this pathway inherits the major weakness of direct guanosine formation from free guanine and ribose. Since the nucleoside step is the true bottleneck, the full nucleotide pathway is not persuasive in its current form.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.86\n- Feedback: This is a strong, well-connected synthesis network with clear hubs, multiple convergent routes to guanine, and unusually good alignment to the modern guanine literature. It correctly emphasizes the experimentally established HCN trunk through DAMN, AICN, and AICA; includes formamide-based production regimes; and captures the major conceptual advance of the Carell FaPy nucleoside pathway rather than relying on implausible direct guanine-ribose glycosylation. Network topology is good: the graph is connected, the target is reached by several independent branches, and the stated hub molecules are mostly valid. Environmental interconnection is also generally good, especially the intended hydrothermal feedstock support for surface chemistry and the use of surface products in biochemical-style nucleoside handling. However, there are notable issues preventing approval at the highest level. The molecule list contains at least one duplicate species entry for formic acid (mol_003 and mol_018), violating the uniqueness rule. Several reactions are chemically compressed or underspecified, especially rxn_002 (formic acid to formamide lacks explicit ammonia), rxn_012 (direct formamide to ribose is weakly supported), and rxn_013 (TAHP formation is too lumped relative to the cited literature). The network summary also states that hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral agents, but the provided reaction list omits them entirely, which is a major formal deficiency under the schema and weakens environmental realism. Literature alignment is otherwise good to very good: the network reflects Sanchez/Ferris/Orgel, Ferris-Orgel photochemistry, Saladino/Barks/Ferus formamide chemistry, and Becker/Carell FaPy chemistry, while avoiding unsupported claims about cyanosulfidic guanine synthesis. Overall, this is an above-average and mostly coherent network, but it falls short of approval because of missing mineral-agent specification, duplicate molecule identity, and a few chemically weak bridging steps.\n- Issues: []\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Guanine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network integrates literature-supported prebiotic routes to guanine across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1 feedstocks and simple organics such as formate and formamide through mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and related vent chemistry. Surface environments then host the experimentally established guanine-forming routes: (i) HCN oligomerization through DAMN, AICN, and AICA with UV-driven branching to guanine; (ii) formamide thermolysis/photochemistry on minerals or under irradiation; and (iii) the Carell formamidopyrimidine/FaPy route that solves the purine glycosylation problem by constructing the purine ring on ribose to give guanosine, followed by hydrolysis to guanine if needed. Biochemical/prebiotic settings connect surface products into nucleosides, nucleotides, and oligomers. The network emphasizes the literature-identified hub molecules HCN, formamide, AICN, AICA, and ribose, includes convergent synthesis to guanine from multiple environments, and avoids unsupported direct free-guanosine glycosylation as a major route.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICA\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2N2/c3-1-2-4\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5N5O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-1,7-dihydro-6H-purin-6-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"guanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H5N5O/c6-5-9-3-2(4(11)10-5)7-1-8-3/h1H,(H4,6,7,8,9,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ribose\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11-1/h2-10H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7N5O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,5,6-triamino-4-hydroxypyrimidine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"TAHP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"variable\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamidopyrimidine derivative\",\n      \"common_name\": \"FaPy intermediate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H13N5O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"9-beta-D-ribofuranosylguanine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"guanosine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H13N5O5/c11-10-14-7-5(8(17)15-10)12-1-13(7)9-6(18)4(16)3(2-19)20-9/h1,3-4,6,9,16-19H,2H2,(H3,11,14,15,17)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanimidamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H3,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH5N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbamimidamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"guanidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH5N3/c2-1(3)4/h(H5,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"PO4H3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H14N5O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"guanosine 5'-monophosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"GMP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"polymer\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"guanosine-containing oligoribonucleotide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"G-rich oligonucleotide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"isocyanic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent setting, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 yields formate/formic acid as a vent feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S and Fe-oxide minerals are established catalysts for CO2 reduction to formate in alkaline vent analog systems, providing plausible upstream C1 feedstocks for later formamide chemistry; this is a connective feedstock step rather than a guanine-specific transformation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007; Saladino et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formation of formamide from formic acid and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor rock-water interactions; dehydration/condensation in mineral pores\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of formic acid with ammonia under mineral-assisted dehydrating conditions gives formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is treated in the guanine literature as a central prebiotic solvent/reactant and can arise from simple C1 feedstocks plus ammonia; this hydrothermal source is included as a necessary feedstock connection to the extensively documented formamide-based guanine chemistry, though the specific vent step is more speculative than the downstream reactions (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2008; Slavova et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide decomposition to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"403K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat or highly concentrated formamide; heating/UV-accessible surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial thermal decomposition of formamide generates HCN and water, feeding HCN oligomerization chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formamide literature emphasizes that heating formamide generates HCN and H2O, which then enter the same purine-forming network as aqueous cyanide chemistry; this decomposition underlies the self-catalytic formamide system (Saladino et al., 2001; Barks et al., 2010; Slavova et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"253-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and TiO2 surfaces for concentration/photochemical exposure\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires HCN concentration above about 0.01 M; can be aided by eutectic concentration near -23.4C or evaporitic concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential oligomerization of HCN through dimer and trimer stages yields the stable tetramer diaminomaleonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAMN is the experimentally established stable HCN tetramer and the main trunk intermediate leading to purines; oligomerization requires concentrated HCN, which the literature shows can be achieved in eutectic freezing or evaporative settings (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Levy et al., 1999; Miyakawa et al., 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization and cyclization of DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic surface and montmorillonite adsorption surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation around 350 nm; DAMN photoisomerizes to DAFN then thermally cyclizes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"DAMN undergoes UV-induced cis-trans isomerization to DAFN followed by cyclization to 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris and Orgel established the DAMN to AICN photochemical conversion via DAFN, with later quantum yield analysis confirming the UV-driven mechanism; AICN is the master branch point for adenine versus guanine formation (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Szabla et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of AICN to AICA\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"moderate water activity; branch-favoring hydrolysis before HCN/formamidine addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile of AICN hydrolyzes to the carboxamide, producing AICA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"AICA is the hydrolysis product of AICN and the required precursor to guanine in the classical Orgel/Ferris pathway; water activity controls whether AICN proceeds toward adenine or guanine (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1968; Jung & Choe, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Annulation of AICA with cyanogen to guanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite adsorption/concentration surface and TiO2-exposed UV-active surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous annulation after AICN hydrolysis; water-catalyzed barrier lowering plausible\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"AICA reacts with cyanogen and water to close the second ring and install the 6-oxo purine framework, yielding guanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical classical guanine-forming step: Sanchez, Ferris, and Orgel demonstrated guanine from AICA with cyanogen, and later computation supported significant water-assisted barrier reduction for the AICN/AICA/cyanogen route (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1968; Jung & Choe, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Drying-mediated guanine formation from AICA and urea\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"338K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals and montmorillonite under drying conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"urea-ammonium-formate-water drying system; about 65C over days\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrating dry-state condensation in urea-containing mixtures enables ring closure to guanine under mild heating.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Drying systems containing urea and ammonium formate have been shown to produce guanine from advanced pyrimidine/purine precursors under mild prebiotic conditions; this route is included as a lower-certainty but literature-grounded drying branch consistent with guanine-forming purine chemistry (Menor-Salvan et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal formamide synthesis of guanine on iron-sulfur minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron-sulfur minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide, 160C for 48 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex thermolysis network in neat formamide produces HCN, NH3, formic acid, urea, and reactive intermediates that converge to purine nucleobases including guanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino and coworkers showed that heating neat formamide with iron-sulfur minerals such as pyrite yields nucleobases including guanine; the chemistry is network-like rather than single-step, but guanine production is experimentally established under these conditions (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2008; Slavova et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-enhanced guanine formation from neat formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"403K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 or no mineral in the original irradiation experiment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"254 nm UV, 130C, about 48 h; mineral surface included here to satisfy required surface-agent schema and reflect TiO2-supported photochemistry literature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation of hot concentrated formamide drives radical and condensation chemistry that produces purine nucleobases including guanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Barks et al. demonstrated guanine formation from neat formamide under 254 nm irradiation at 130C even without added minerals, while TiO2 surface photochemistry independently supports guanine-like product generation under band-gap excitation; the route is therefore literature-supported as a UV surface pathway (Barks et al., 2010; Senanayake & Idriss, 2006).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Impact/plasma conversion of formamide to guanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable transient high-energy\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to transient shock conditions\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces plus high-energy irradiation/plasma\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"impact-like plasma or proton irradiation; meteorite/mineral powders act as catalytic surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy processing of formamide produces radical cyanide chemistry and a broad nucleobase inventory including guanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Laser-plasma and proton-irradiation studies showed guanine among nucleobase products from formamide under impact/cosmic-ray analog conditions; this is an episodic but experimentally validated surface source of guanine (Ferus et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized ribose formation and accumulation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formose-like sugar chemistry with borate stabilization and evaporative concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived carbonyl chemistry and formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde pools feed sugar formation, while borate selectively stabilizes ribose.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ribose stabilization by borate minerals is strongly supported and is essential for later nucleoside formation; while the full sugar network is broader than a single reaction, borate-enabled ribose availability is a central literature-supported prerequisite for purine nucleosides (Ricardo et al., 2004; Furukawa et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Construction of triaminohydroxypyrimidine precursor from HCN-derived feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals under wet-dry cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"multicomponent HCN oligomer/guanidine/formic acid chemistry leading to aminopyrimidines\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization products react with guanidine and formylating C1 species to build aminopyrimidine scaffolds relevant to guanine/FaPy chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Carell's guanine nucleoside pathway begins from aminopyrimidine precursors accessible from HCN oligomers, guanidine, and formylating chemistry; this node represents that experimentally motivated precursor assembly without invoking unsupported free-base glycosylation (Becker et al., 2016; Becker et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction/formylation of pyrimidine precursor to FaPy intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron in dilute formic acid, with drying surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles; Fe/Ni reduction in dilute formic acid; physical enrichment by precipitation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dry-state nitrosation/reduction/formylation chemistry converts aminopyrimidine precursors into formamidopyrimidines that are poised for ribose condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Becker et al. showed that wet-dry cycles with nitrite handling and reduction by elemental iron and nickel in dilute formic acid furnish FaPy intermediates from aminopyrimidines; this is the key pre-glycosylation solution to purine nucleoside formation (Becker et al., 2018; Becker et al., 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Dry-state condensation of FaPy intermediate with ribose to guanosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry state condensation around 100C followed by basic aqueous rehydration; strong N9 regioselectivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The purine ring is completed on a pre-attached sugar during dry-state condensation, solving the guanine glycosylation/regiochemistry problem and yielding guanosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the hallmark Carell result: FaPy intermediates condense with ribose in the dry state to give N9-purine nucleosides with about 60% yield and high regioselectivity, circumventing the poor direct coupling of free guanine and ribose (Becker et al., 2016; Becker et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic liberation of guanine from guanosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic hydrolytic turnover in pools or during geochemical cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the N-glycosidic bond releases guanine and ribose from guanosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although the literature emphasizes guanosine formation rather than deliberate hydrolysis, this connecting step is chemically necessary to relate the Carell nucleoside route to free guanine as the target and is included as a conservative network linkage consistent with known nucleoside lability under prebiotic aqueous cycling; this step is more general prebiotic chemistry than a guanine-specific named experiment (Becker et al., 2016; Becker et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphorylation of guanosine to GMP\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-heating or evaporative phosphorylation regime; geochemical cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrating phosphorylation converts guanosine into guanosine monophosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Unified prebiotic nucleoside-to-nucleotide chemistry including guanosine phosphates was demonstrated under geochemically coherent conditions in the Carell framework; this extends the guanine network into biologically relevant nucleotide space (Becker et al., 2019; Furukawa et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Template-directed oligomerization of GMP to G-rich oligoribonucleotide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"293-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling, mildly alkaline conditions, mineral interfaces can assist\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated or cyclic nucleotide analog behavior under repeated dehydration/rehydration enables phosphodiester bond formation and oligomer growth.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Recent wet-dry cycling studies show especially favorable polymerization behavior for guanosine-based nucleotides, while clay-assisted oligomerization literature establishes prebiotic template/polymer growth relevance for purines; this places guanine products into downstream prebiotic assembly (Huang & Ferris, 2006; ACS Central Science, 2025 as summarized in the report).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical HCN-to-guanine route from hydrothermal C1 feedstocks\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies formic acid and formamide, which decompose to HCN; HCN oligomerizes to DAMN, is photoconverted to AICN, hydrolyzed to AICA, and annulated with cyanogen to guanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN eutectic/evaporitic concentration route to guanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Concentrated HCN formed from formamide in surface settings enters the DAMN-AICN-AICA-cyanogen sequence without explicit hydrothermal upstream detail.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"AICA plus urea drying branch\",\n      \"description\": \"The classical HCN trunk reaches AICA, then drying chemistry with urea furnishes guanine under mild heating.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal formamide mineral-catalyzed guanine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Neat formamide heated with iron-sulfur minerals yields guanine directly through a complex self-catalytic decomposition network.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-enhanced hot formamide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermally sourced formamide is concentrated in surface settings and irradiated with UV at 130C to generate guanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Impact/plasma formamide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide produced from simple feedstocks undergoes high-energy impact-like or proton-irradiation chemistry to generate guanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Carell FaPy route from HCN-derived aminopyrimidines to guanosine then guanine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-derived chemistry plus guanidine and formylating feedstocks build an aminopyrimidine, which is converted to a FaPy intermediate and condensed with ribose to guanosine; hydrolysis yields free guanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-formamide-assisted FaPy route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formamide and formic acid feed surface wet-dry cycles that generate FaPy intermediates and then guanosine, followed by guanine release.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"FaPy route extended to nucleotide space\",\n      \"description\": \"The Carell route yields guanosine, which is phosphorylated to GMP and thereby embeds guanine into nucleotide chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"FaPy route to guanine-containing oligomer precursors\",\n      \"description\": \"Guanosine formed through the FaPy pathway is phosphorylated and incorporated into G-rich oligoribonucleotide products in biochemical cycling environments.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Guanine", "overall_strategy": "This network integrates literature-supported prebiotic routes to guanine across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1 feedstocks and simple organics such as formate and formamide through mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and related vent chemistry. Surface environments then host the experimentally established guanine-forming routes: (i) HCN oligomerization through DAMN, AICN, and AICA with UV-driven branching to guanine; (ii) formamide thermolysis/photochemistry on minerals or under irradiation; and (iii) the Carell formamidopyrimidine/FaPy route that solves the purine glycosylation problem by constructing the purine ring on ribose to give guanosine, followed by hydrolysis to guanine if needed. Biochemical/prebiotic settings connect surface products into nucleosides, nucleotides, and oligomers. The network emphasizes the literature-identified hub molecules HCN, formamide, AICN, AICA, and ribose, includes convergent synthesis to guanine from multiple environments, and avoids unsupported direct free-guanosine glycosylation as a major route.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H6N4O", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide", "common_name": "AICA", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2N2", "iupac_name": "ethanedinitrile", "common_name": "cyanogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2N2/c3-1-2-4", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "carbamide", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H5N5O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-1,7-dihydro-6H-purin-6-one", "common_name": "guanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N5O/c6-5-9-3-2(4(11)10-5)7-1-8-3/h1H,(H4,6,7,8,9,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H10O5", "iupac_name": "ribose", "common_name": "ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11-1/h2-10H,1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H7N5O", "iupac_name": "2,5,6-triamino-4-hydroxypyrimidine", "common_name": "TAHP", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "variable", "iupac_name": "formamidopyrimidine derivative", "common_name": "FaPy intermediate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C10H13N5O5", "iupac_name": "9-beta-D-ribofuranosylguanine", "common_name": "guanosine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H13N5O5/c11-10-14-7-5(8(17)15-10)12-1-13(7)9-6(18)4(16)3(2-19)20-9/h1,3-4,6,9,16-19H,2H2,(H3,11,14,15,17)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "CH3N", "iupac_name": "methanimidamide", "common_name": "formamidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H3,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH5N3", "iupac_name": "carbamimidamide", "common_name": "guanidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH5N3/c2-1(3)4/h(H5,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "PO4H3", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C10H14N5O8P", "iupac_name": "guanosine 5'-monophosphate", "common_name": "GMP", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "polymer", "iupac_name": "guanosine-containing oligoribonucleotide", "common_name": "G-rich oligonucleotide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "isocyanic acid", "common_name": "cyanate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formic acid", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent setting, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 yields formate/formic acid as a vent feedstock.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S and Fe-oxide minerals are established catalysts for CO2 reduction to formate in alkaline vent analog systems, providing plausible upstream C1 feedstocks for later formamide chemistry; this is a connective feedstock step rather than a guanine-specific transformation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007; Saladino et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal formation of formamide from formic acid and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_020"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor rock-water interactions; dehydration/condensation in mineral pores"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of formic acid with ammonia under mineral-assisted dehydrating conditions gives formamide.", "reasoning": "Formamide is treated in the guanine literature as a central prebiotic solvent/reactant and can arise from simple C1 feedstocks plus ammonia; this hydrothermal source is included as a necessary feedstock connection to the extensively documented formamide-based guanine chemistry, though the specific vent step is more speculative than the downstream reactions (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2008; Slavova et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formamide decomposition to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "403K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "neat or highly concentrated formamide; heating/UV-accessible surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Partial thermal decomposition of formamide generates HCN and water, feeding HCN oligomerization chemistry.", "reasoning": "The formamide literature emphasizes that heating formamide generates HCN and H2O, which then enter the same purine-forming network as aqueous cyanide chemistry; this decomposition underlies the self-catalytic formamide system (Saladino et al., 2001; Barks et al., 2010; Slavova et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "253-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and TiO2 surfaces for concentration/photochemical exposure", "aqueous": "true", "other": "requires HCN concentration above about 0.01 M; can be aided by eutectic concentration near -23.4C or evaporitic concentration"}, "mechanism": "Sequential oligomerization of HCN through dimer and trimer stages yields the stable tetramer diaminomaleonitrile.", "reasoning": "DAMN is the experimentally established stable HCN tetramer and the main trunk intermediate leading to purines; oligomerization requires concentrated HCN, which the literature shows can be achieved in eutectic freezing or evaporative settings (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Levy et al., 1999; Miyakawa et al., 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV photoisomerization and cyclization of DAMN to AICN", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalytic surface and montmorillonite adsorption surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation around 350 nm; DAMN photoisomerizes to DAFN then thermally cyclizes"}, "mechanism": "DAMN undergoes UV-induced cis-trans isomerization to DAFN followed by cyclization to 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile.", "reasoning": "Ferris and Orgel established the DAMN to AICN photochemical conversion via DAFN, with later quantum yield analysis confirming the UV-driven mechanism; AICN is the master branch point for adenine versus guanine formation (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Szabla et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrolysis of AICN to AICA", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "moderate water activity; branch-favoring hydrolysis before HCN/formamidine addition"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile of AICN hydrolyzes to the carboxamide, producing AICA.", "reasoning": "AICA is the hydrolysis product of AICN and the required precursor to guanine in the classical Orgel/Ferris pathway; water activity controls whether AICN proceeds toward adenine or guanine (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1968; Jung & Choe, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Annulation of AICA with cyanogen to guanine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite adsorption/concentration surface and TiO2-exposed UV-active surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous annulation after AICN hydrolysis; water-catalyzed barrier lowering plausible"}, "mechanism": "AICA reacts with cyanogen and water to close the second ring and install the 6-oxo purine framework, yielding guanine.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical classical guanine-forming step: Sanchez, Ferris, and Orgel demonstrated guanine from AICA with cyanogen, and later computation supported significant water-assisted barrier reduction for the AICN/AICA/cyanogen route (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1968; Jung & Choe, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Drying-mediated guanine formation from AICA and urea", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "338K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals and montmorillonite under drying conditions", "aqueous": "false", "other": "urea-ammonium-formate-water drying system; about 65C over days"}, "mechanism": "Concentrating dry-state condensation in urea-containing mixtures enables ring closure to guanine under mild heating.", "reasoning": "Drying systems containing urea and ammonium formate have been shown to produce guanine from advanced pyrimidine/purine precursors under mild prebiotic conditions; this route is included as a lower-certainty but literature-grounded drying branch consistent with guanine-forming purine chemistry (Menor-Salvan et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Thermal formamide synthesis of guanine on iron-sulfur minerals", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "iron-sulfur minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "neat formamide, 160C for 48 h"}, "mechanism": "Complex thermolysis network in neat formamide produces HCN, NH3, formic acid, urea, and reactive intermediates that converge to purine nucleobases including guanine.", "reasoning": "Saladino and coworkers showed that heating neat formamide with iron-sulfur minerals such as pyrite yields nucleobases including guanine; the chemistry is network-like rather than single-step, but guanine production is experimentally established under these conditions (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2008; Slavova et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "UV-enhanced guanine formation from neat formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "403K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 or no mineral in the original irradiation experiment", "aqueous": "false", "other": "254 nm UV, 130C, about 48 h; mineral surface included here to satisfy required surface-agent schema and reflect TiO2-supported photochemistry literature"}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation of hot concentrated formamide drives radical and condensation chemistry that produces purine nucleobases including guanine.", "reasoning": "Barks et al. demonstrated guanine formation from neat formamide under 254 nm irradiation at 130C even without added minerals, while TiO2 surface photochemistry independently supports guanine-like product generation under band-gap excitation; the route is therefore literature-supported as a UV surface pathway (Barks et al., 2010; Senanayake & Idriss, 2006)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Impact/plasma conversion of formamide to guanine", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable transient high-energy", "pressure": "1 atm to transient shock conditions", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces plus high-energy irradiation/plasma", "aqueous": "false", "other": "impact-like plasma or proton irradiation; meteorite/mineral powders act as catalytic surfaces"}, "mechanism": "High-energy processing of formamide produces radical cyanide chemistry and a broad nucleobase inventory including guanine.", "reasoning": "Laser-plasma and proton-irradiation studies showed guanine among nucleobase products from formamide under impact/cosmic-ray analog conditions; this is an episodic but experimentally validated surface source of guanine (Ferus et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Borate-stabilized ribose formation and accumulation", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "formose-like sugar chemistry with borate stabilization and evaporative concentration"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived carbonyl chemistry and formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde pools feed sugar formation, while borate selectively stabilizes ribose.", "reasoning": "Ribose stabilization by borate minerals is strongly supported and is essential for later nucleoside formation; while the full sugar network is broader than a single reaction, borate-enabled ribose availability is a central literature-supported prerequisite for purine nucleosides (Ricardo et al., 2004; Furukawa et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Construction of triaminohydroxypyrimidine precursor from HCN-derived feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_017", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "