ather than a central prebiotic landscape pathway. Again, formamide sourcing remains the weak point.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Treat this as a contingency or exogenous high-energy route rather than a core pathway.\",\n        \"Include explicit impact/plasma energy context and product-complexity caveat.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.71,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway correctly reflects the important Carell insight that guanosine formation is best achieved through FaPy intermediates rather than direct glycosylation of free guanine. The dry-state FaPy + ribose -> guanosine step is excellent and literature-aligned. However, the route is weakened by an implausible ribose step: direct HCN + H2O -> ribose is not chemically valid as written, even with borate stabilization. Ribose should arise from formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde/formose chemistry with borate, not directly from HCN. The final hydrolysis of guanosine to guanine is possible but not the key literature endpoint; the stronger endpoint is guanosine/GMP itself.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\",\n        \"rxn_016\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace rxn_012 with a formose/borate-based sugar pathway.\",\n        \"Align precursor details with Becker-Carell chemistry more closely, including nitroso intermediate and Fe/Ni reduction where relevant.\",\n        \"Consider guanosine or GMP as the principal target in this bran